ROS 2 Custom Messages – Complete Notes
What is a Message in ROS 2?

A message is a data structure used by ROS 2 nodes to exchange information through a topic.

Think of it like a parcel being delivered.

Publisher ---> Topic ---> Subscriber
Publisher = Sender
Topic = Delivery route
Message = Parcel containing data
Subscriber = Receiver

The message defines what data can be sent.

Example: Standard String Message

Earlier we used:

from example_interfaces.msg import String

The structure of this message is:

string data

This means the message contains only one field called data.

Example:

msg = String()
msg.data = "Hello ROS2"

The subscriber receives:

topic_message.data
Why Create a Custom Message?

Suppose we want to send:

"The ROS time is..."
1781358432

A standard String message cannot hold both values.

We need our own message type.

Creating a Custom Message
Step 1: Create a msg Folder

Navigate to the package root:

cd ~/ros2_ws/src/part1_pubsub

Create a message directory:

mkdir msg
Step 2: Create a Message File

Create:

touch msg/Example.msg
Step 3: Define the Message

Open:

msg/Example.msg

Add:

string info
int32 time

This defines a new message type called:

Example

with two fields:

Field	Type
info	string
time	int32
Visual Representation
Example Message
├── info : string
└── time : int32

Example instance:

msg = Example()

msg.info = "The ROS time is..."
msg.time = 1781358432
Why Run Colcon Build?

The file:

Example.msg

only describes the message.

ROS must generate Python code from it.

Running:

colcon build

creates the required Python classes automatically.

Without building, this import will fail:

from part1_pubsub.msg import Example
Modifying CMakeLists.txt

Add:

find_package(rosidl_default_generators REQUIRED)

rosidl_generate_interfaces(${PROJECT_NAME}
  "msg/Example.msg"
)

Place these before:

ament_package()
Modifying package.xml

Add:

<buildtool_depend>rosidl_default_generators</buildtool_depend>

<exec_depend>rosidl_default_runtime</exec_depend>

<member_of_group>
  rosidl_interface_packages
</member_of_group>

Place them above:

<export>
Build the Message

From the workspace root:

cd ~/ros2_ws

Build:

colcon build --packages-select part1_pubsub --symlink-install

Source the workspace:

source install/setup.bash

or

source ~/.bashrc

(if already added there)

Verify the Message

List available messages:

ros2 interface list -m

You should find:

part1_pubsub/msg/Example

Display the structure:

ros2 interface show part1_pubsub/msg/Example

Output:

string info
int32 time
Custom Publisher

Import:

from part1_pubsub.msg import Example

Create the publisher:

self.my_publisher = self.create_publisher(
    msg_type=Example,
    topic="my_topic",
    qos_profile=10,
)

Create and fill the message:

topic_msg = Example()

topic_msg.info = "The ROS time is..."
topic_msg.time = ros_time[0]

Publish:

self.my_publisher.publish(topic_msg)
Custom Subscriber

Import:

from part1_pubsub.msg import Example

Subscribe:

self.my_subscriber = self.create_subscription(
    msg_type=Example,
    topic="my_topic",
    callback=self.msg_callback,
    qos_profile=10,
)
Callback Function

Old String message:

topic_message.data

Custom message:

topic_message.info
topic_message.time

Example:

def msg_callback(self, topic_message):

    self.get_logger().info(
        f"Info: {topic_message.info}"
    )

    self.get_logger().info(
        f"Time: {topic_message.time}"
    )
Why Did We Copy Publisher and Subscriber?

We created:

publisher.py
subscriber.py

using:

example_interfaces/msg/String

For Exercise 8 we create:

custom_msg_publisher.py
custom_msg_subscriber.py

using:

part1_pubsub/msg/Example

This allows us to keep the old example while learning custom messages.

Installing New Executables

Add to CMakeLists.txt:

install(PROGRAMS
  scripts/basic_velocity_control.py
  scripts/stop_me.py
  scripts/publisher.py
  scripts/subscriber.py
  scripts/custom_msg_publisher.py
  scripts/custom_msg_subscriber.py
  DESTINATION lib/${PROJECT_NAME}
)
Rebuild After Adding New Scripts
colcon build --packages-select part1_pubsub --symlink-install

Source:

source install/setup.bash
Running the Nodes

Terminal 1:

ros2 run part1_pubsub custom_msg_publisher.py

Terminal 2:

ros2 run part1_pubsub custom_msg_subscriber.py
Key Concept to Remember
Message = Structure of Data

Topic = Communication Channel

Publisher = Sends Messages

Subscriber = Receives Messages

For communication to work:

Publisher and Subscriber
must use the same Topic
and the same Message Type.

Example:

Publisher
    |
    | Example Message
    |
 /my_topic
    |
    v
Subscriber

Message content:

Example
├── info = "The ROS time is..."
└── time = 1781358432

This is the foundation of communication in ROS 2 and is used everywhere—from robot velocity commands to camera images, LiDAR scans, GPS data, and navigation information.
